      {
        "id": 2501600,
        "name": "Robert Pavlovich",
        "username": "Robert_Pavlovich",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/robert_pavlovich/{size}/1929_2.png",
        "created_at": "2018-10-14T17:44:27.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Took part in an epic celebratory dinner Friday night @ Officine Brera. Some great wines and comraderie. Here\u2019s all the data.</p>\n<p>Highlights from the dinner included a 99\u2019 and 82\u2019 Salon comparison, the <strong>1999 Salon</strong> was still primary trying to turn secondary but pretty unmoved on that front. Built like a tank with really nice potential. Wait 5-10 years easy. The <strong>1982 Salon</strong> was very expressive with aromas full of yeast and brioche but still a good underlying freshness throughout. Great fruit, late secondary expression, with a haunting lower impact finish.</p>\n<p><strong>2009 Raveneau Blanchots</strong> was a bit over the top for me, big and tropical and the alcohol wasn\u2019t very well hidden. But then chef Angelo made a Thai snapper sashimi that made for a perfect pairing.</p>\n<p><strong>2005 PYCM Batard Montrachet</strong> - Premox\u2019d, though I\u2019ve seen worse this was a shame.</p>\n<p><strong>2010 Ramonet Batard Montrachet</strong> was a beautiful white Burg, clearly showing elegance and restraint in contrast to the Raveneau, but not without power itself. Shows the balance of fruit and cut that I look for in top level whites, and even though it\u2019s a bit reduced, it shows a nice, expansive finish. Neck and neck for the best white of the night, though opinions were somewhat mixed. I have a bottle in the cellar that I\u2019ll mark for 2025.</p>\n<p><strong>2011 Bouchard Montrachet</strong>\u2026having had the 13\u2019 recently I had a sense of the style going in, tightly coiled and restrained with that great duality of elegance and power. And that\u2019s exactly how it showed, the 11\u2019 (after an hour+ double decant) showed nice salinity and florals on the nose. Similar on the palate, it has that mineral spine with expressive fruit and great energy on the chalk and mineral laden finish. Evaporates gracefully and you want more. Softer edges and more graceful than the Ramonet, which could be as much a difference in vintage as vineyard.</p>\n<p><strong>2013 Domaine Thenard Montrachet</strong>. Showed as more fruit forward than the other two GC\u2019s, flashing its class and pedigree, also really nice power on entry into the mid palate but not the complete wine that the other GC\u2019s were.</p>\n<p>          <iframe width=\"640\" height=\"738\" frameborder=\"0\" data-unsanitized-src=\"https://instagram.com/p/Bo4xdj8hXJ4/embed\" seamless=\"seamless\" sandbox=\"allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-forms allow-popups allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox allow-presentation\"></iframe>\n</p>\n<p>About the reds\u2026</p>\n<p>We started with a <strong>1978 Domaine Michel Gaunoux Pommard Rugiens</strong>. As it was laced with sweet dark red fruit, chef brought out a fruit tart with blueberries and the match was killer. Concentration, ripeness, and vividly fresh nature of the wine was remarkable. A great, pristine bottle that received a WOTN vote for reds.</p>\n<p>Next were the 93\u2019 Georges Mugneret GC\u2019s. The Domaine that is now Mugneret-Gibourg.</p>\n<p>The <strong>1993 Georges Mugneret Ruchottes Chambertin</strong> showed classic dark fruit, really saturating the palate on entry and mid palate, quite a bit of sweetness to the fruit with good earth and spice support, though fell off a bit toward the back.</p>\n<p><strong>1993 Georges Mugneret Clos Vougeot</strong> had more freshness integrated in to the wine, good fruit that was notably less sweet than the Ruchottes, it had a hard to explain, umami character to it, and it also left the impression it might be very long lived. Shows why it\u2019s the flagship wine of the estate, it\u2019s an intruiging wine that makes you think. Would love to revisit in 10 years.</p>\n<p>The 01\u2019 Hudelot-Noellat\u2019s were also a treat to taste side by side. The <strong>2001 Hudelot-Noellat Romanee Saint Vivant</strong> was a bit of a shock to the senses, coming off the elegant Clos Vougeot the RSV was laced with high concentration dark red fruit and spice. It had slightly elevated alcohol that distracted a bit however. This set the stage for the <strong>2001 Hudelot-Noellat Richebourg</strong>, which really shined, showing more balance and it just happened to be singing. It seemed to have a lot of everything without being over done.</p>\n<p>On to the Barolo\u2019s\u2026any help as far as to what blends of vineyards we might have been drinking would be appreciated.</p>\n<p><strong>1964 Francesco Rinaldi Barolo</strong>\u2026kept thinking we must be tasting a blend of Brunate, Cannubi, and other vineyards and it sure seemed that way, with very little rusticity, it lead with its freshness and was drinking great.</p>\n<p><strong>1964 Giuseppe Rinaldi Barolo</strong>. Here everything came in to greater focus, the concentrated dark red fruit would of had us believe it was a 1990, it was that young and vivid.</p>\n<p><strong>1964 Minuto Barolo</strong>. While this didn\u2019t show as clean as some of the others, it was still in very nice shape, unleashing a balsamic note that reminded me of a 61\u2019 Oddero from a few years ago, and though this Minuto didn\u2019t quite have the magic of the Oddero I remember, it still held our attention.</p>\n<p><strong>1971 Giuseppe Mascarello Barolo</strong>. What a treat to try this, the bottle was in excellent shape from what I recall, with more fruit than the Francesco Rinaldi but not quite as big as the Giuseppe, it was sitting in a great spot and if there are more bottles like this, they should sail on for a long time. Would love to be able to try again with greater focus.</p>",
